 = %\n|demographics2_title1           = 0 to 14\n|demographics2_info1            = %\n|demographics2_title2           = 15 to 64\n|demographics2_info2            = %\n|demographics2_title3           = 65 or older\n|demographics2_info3            = %\n|timezone               = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|utc_offset             = +2\n|timezone_DST           = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST         = +3\n|coordinates            = {{coord|60|18|N|022|18|E|region:FI|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type       = Postal code\n}}\n\n'''Pargas''' ({{IPA-sv|\u02c8p\u0251r\u02d0\u0261\u0251s|langfi}}; {{lang-fi|Parainen}}, {{IPA-fi|\u02c8p\u0251r\u0251i\u032fnen|pron}}) is a former [[List of cities and towns in Finland|town]] and [[List of former municipalities of Finland|municipality]] in south-western Finland. On 1 January 2009, it was consolidated with [[Houtsk\u00e4r]], [[Ini\u00f6]], [[Korpo]] and [[Nagu, Finland|Nagu]] to form the new municipality of [[V\u00e4st\u00e5boland]] (since renamed to ''[[Pargas]]'').\n\nIt is known as the \"capital\" of the archipelago of Turku and had been called a town since 1977. It is located in the [[provinces of Finland|province]] of [[Western Finland]] and is part of the [[Southwest Finland]] [[regions of Finland|region]]. The town had a population of 12,266 (as of 31 December 2008)<ref name=\"population count\" /> and covered a land area of {{convert|273.18|km2|sqmi}}.<ref name=\"total area\" /> The [[population density]] was {{convert|44.9|PD/km2}}.\n\nThe municipality was [[bilingual]], with the majority (54%) being [[Swedish language|Swedish]] and the minority (45%) [[Finnish language|Finnish]] speakers.\n\nThe city has many little suburbs around it, including Kirjala and Lielax.\n[[Image:Airisto, Parainen, Finland-a.jpg|thumb|left|280px|View from Airisto harbour, Storm\u00e4l\u00f6]]\n\n==International relations==\n{{Main|List of twin towns and sister cities in Finland}}\n\n===Twin towns \u2014 Sister cities===\nThe sister cities of Pargas are\n\n* {{flagicon|Sweden}} [[Haninge Municipality|Haninge]], Sweden\n* {{flagicon|Norway}} [[Ulstein]], Norway\n* {{flagicon|Russia}} [[Chudovo, Chudovsky District, Novgorod Oblast|Chudovo]], Russia\n* {{flagicon|Estonia}} [[K\u00e4rdla]], Estonia\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{commonscat-inline|Pargas}}\n* {{wikivoyage-inline|Pargas}}\n* [http://www.pargas.fi/ Official website] \u2013 in Swedish and Finnish\n\n{{FinlandProper}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places disestablished in 2009]]\n[[Category:2009 disestablishments in Finland]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Finland]]\n[[Category:Former municipalities of Finland]]\n[[Category:Pargas]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pargas_(former_municipality)"}
{"title_page": "Blair Imani", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Blair Imani\n| birth_name = Blair Elizabeth Brown\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1993|10|31|mf=yes}}<ref name=birthdate>{{cite tweet |last= Imani |first=Blair |user=BlairImani |number=1056636517752422403 |date=October 28, 2018 |title= My birthday is on October 31, Halloween. I will be 25 this year.|access-date=October 29, 2018 }}</ref>\n| image = Blair Imani at LoveLoud 2018 (42462971960).jpg\n| caption = Blair Imani in 2018\n| education = [[Louisiana State University]]\n| known_for = Activism\n| movement = Black Lives Matter\n| website = https://blairimani.com\n}}\n\n'''Blair Imani''' (born '''Blair Elizabeth Brown''', October 31, 1993)<ref name=birthdate/> is an [[African-American]] [[Muslim]] [[queer]], author and [[activist]]. She was Executive Director of \"Equality for HER\", a now defunct feminist organisation.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Matthew|last=Corkins|url=http://observer.com/2017/02/blair-imani-black-muslim-activist-womens-march/|title=In Trump Era, Islam\u2019s Tolerance Helps Restless Activist Survive|date=February 19, 2017|work=Observer|access-date=April 18, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> She is a member of the [[Black Lives Matter]] movement, and is known for her voice on [[Twitter]] and [[Instagram]] and for protesting the [[shooting of Alton Sterling]] and [[Executive Order 13769]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/muslim-women-you-should-be-following-on-twitter-because-we-need-their-voices-now-more-than-ever-34101|title=Muslim Women You Should Be Following On Twitter, Because We Need Their Voices Now More Than Ever|last=Florio|first=Gina M.|work=Bustle|date=January 30, 2017|access-date=April 18, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Imani has written for ''[[HuffPost]]'' and ''[[Vice Media|VICE]].''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_us/article/why-activist-blair-imani-will-no-longer-wear-hijab-post-trump|title=Why activist Blair Imani will no longer wear hijab post-Trump|first=Blair|last=Imani|work=i-D|publisher=Vice Media|access-date=April 18, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/one-month-ago-in-baton-rouge_us_57a7d416e4b0c94bd3c9ce0c|title=One Month Ago In Baton Rouge|last=Imani|first=Blair|date=August 10, 2016|website=HuffPost|language=en-US|access-date=April 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nImani gained recognition for her arrest following the [[shooting of Alton Sterling]] in Baton Rouge, Louisiana, and her continued activism at the [[Intersectionality|intersection]] of [[Black people|Black]] and Muslim identity.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thefourohfive.com/culture/article/discussing-the-resistance-with-blair-imani-149|title=Discussing the Resistance with Blair Imani|last=Bynum-Reid|first=Dierra|work=The 405|access-date=April 18, 2017|date=March 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Education and career==\nImani graduated from [[Louisiana State University]] in 2015.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2016/07/14/baton-rouge-police-sued-arrest-peaceful-protesters/|title=Baton Rouge Police Sued Over Arrest of Peaceful Protesters|last=Mackey2016-07-14T15:35:14+00:00|first=Robert MackeyRobert|website=The Intercept|access-date=2017-04-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, she worked as a Press Officer for [[Planned Parenthood|Planned Parenthood Action Fund]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.plannedparenthoodaction.org/blog/donald-trump-bragged-about-sexual-assault-we-wont-let-him-normalize-it|title=Donald Trump Bragged About Sexual Assault \u2014 But We Won\u2019t Let Him Normalize It|website=www.plannedparenthoodaction.org|language=en|access-date=2017-04-18}}</ref> She is presently the Civic Action & Campaign Lead at [[Do Something|DoSomething.org]], the largest tech company exclusively for young people and social change.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dosomething.org/us/about/our-team|title=Our Team {{!}} DoSomething.org {{!}} Volunteer for Social Change|website=www.dosomething.org|language=en|access-date=2017-08-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/better/pop-culture/7-ways-be-better-activist-ncna791856|title=How to be an activist (no experience required)|work=NBC News|access-date=2017-08-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nImani is the author of ''Modern HERstory: Stories of Women and Nonbinary People Rewriting History'', published by [[Ten Speed Press]] on October 16, 2018. The book is illustrated by Monique Le and \"spotlights 70 overlooked but important [[people of color]], [[queer|queer people]], [[transgender|trans people]], [[disability|disabled people]], and more who are changing the world this very moment.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://penguinrandomhouseeducation.com/book/?isbn=9780399582240|title=Modern HERstory: Stories of Women and Nonbinary People Rewriting History|last=Imani|first=Blair|date=October 16, 2018|website=penguinrandomhouseeducation.com|publisher=Ten Speed Press|access-date=October 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glaad.org/blog/blair-imanis-modern-herstory-changes-narrative-social-justice-include-women-and-nonbinary|title=Blair Imani's \"Modern HERstory\" changes the narrative of social justice to include women and nonbinary notables|date=2018-11-27|website=GLAAD|language=en|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sanfranciscobookreview.com/product/modern-herstory-stories-of-women-and-nonbinary-people-rewriting-history/|title=Modern HERstory: Stories of Women and Nonbinary People Rewriting History|last=Winter|first=Kevin|website=[[San Francisco Book Review]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/life/2018/08/modern-herstory-unsung-activists/|title=\u2018Modern HERstory\u2019 Amplifies the Voices of Unsung Activists|last=Williams|first=Austin|date=August 8, 2018|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/authors-parents-go-celebrate-release-book-modern-herstory-cutest-thing-twitter-seen-015400116.html|title=Author's parents go all out to celebrate the release of her 'Modern HERstory' book, and it's the sweetest thing Twitter has seen|last=Schreiber|first=Hope|date=October 10, 2018|website=Yahoo Lifestyle|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.slj.com/?reviewDetail=modern-herstory-stories-of-women-and-nonbinary-people-rewriting-history|title=Modern HERstory: Stories of Women and Nonbinary People Rewriting History|last=Schembri|first=Pamela|website=School Library Journal|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref>\n\n==Activism in Baton Rouge==\n[[File:Blair_Imani_at_Baton_Rouge_Rally.jpg|thumb|290x290px|Blair Imani at Baton Rouge rally in protest of the police shooting of Alton Sterling]]\nOn July 10, 2016, in the aftermath of the shooting of Alton Sterling, Imani took part in a protest in [[Baton Rouge]], Louisiana. While peacefully protesting, she was arrested with her partner Akeem Muhammad.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/07/13/485895800/baton-rouge-protester-on-arrest-i-didnt-know-if-i-was-going-to-survive|title=Baton Rouge Protester On Arrest: 'I Didn't Know If I Was Going To Survive'|website=NPR.org|access-date=2017-04-18}}</ref> In an interview with ''The Intercept'', Imani detailed her encounter with Baton Rouge [[SWAT]] officers. She claimed that she was trampled and threatened verbally. She was photographed screaming as she was carried away by special force officers.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nWhile being detained, one officer ordered: \"really give it to her,\" and another officer removed her hijab.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Imani |first1=Blair |title=\"One Month Ago in Baton Rouge\" |url=http://www2.latech.edu/~bmagee/louisiana_anthology/texts/imani/imani--one-month-ago.html |website=Louisiana Anthology |accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nLess than a week after her arrest, Imani helped organize a vigil with the Louisiana State University Student Body Association in response to and in honor of the [[2016 shooting of Baton Rouge police officers|murder of three Baton Rouge police officers]]. In an article in ''[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]]'', she said, \"All violence is wrong,\" and that she is against all brutality, including violence against police officers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/news/baton_rouge_officer_shooting/article_e40669a4-4d3b-11e6-9bd9-378cde7cc0f8.html|title=Woman arrested in Alton Sterling protests is key organizer of fallen officers vigil|last=Allen|first=Rebekah|work=The Advocate|access-date=2017-04-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\n\n==Black and Muslim identity==\n\nImani converted to Islam in 2015 following feelings of discomfort in Christian churches and finding solace within Islam. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Hagen |first1=Sofie |title=\"60. Blair Imani - They Took My Hijab Away\" |url=https://mohpod.libsyn.com/60-blair-imani-they-took-my-hijab-away |website=Made of Human Podcast |accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nDescribing her decision to change her name, she explained that she chose the name Imani \"because Imani means 'my faith' and it's one of the days of Kwanzaa, it's also a Swahili word as well as an Arabic word, and I felt like it encapsulated my journey to Islam.\" <ref>{{cite web |last1=Aguilera |first1=Ramsey |title=\"Life as a Queer Muslim in 2019 with Blair Imani\" |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iUujhLMu-RY |website=Youtube |publisher=Youtube |accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the run up to the 2016 presidential election, Imani spoke about the intersection of Black and Muslim identity.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/602/the-sun-comes-up?act=6|title=Times Square|work=This American Life|access-date=2017-04-18}}</ref>\n\nImani waited one year after converting to wear the hijab<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hagen |first1=Sofie |title=\"60. Blair Imani - They Took My Hijab Away\" |url=https://mohpod.libsyn.com/60-blair-imani-they-took-my-hijab-away |website=Made of Human Podcast |accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref> \nand briefly stopped wearing it following the 2016 election.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Corkins |first1=Matthew |title=In Trump Era, Islam's Tolerance Helps Restless Activist Survive |url=https://observer.com/2017/02/blair-imani-black-muslim-activist-womens-march/ |website=Observer |publisher=Observer |accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe appeared on MSNBC's ''The Point'' hosted by Ari Melber on April 2, 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc-news/watch/growing-up-trump-the-next-generation-speaks-out-912401475510|title=Growing Up Trump: The next generation speaks out|work=MSNBC|access-date=2017-04-18}}</ref> She presented with activist [[Kwame Rose]] at the [[Harvard University]] [[John F. Kennedy School of Government|Kennedy School]]'s 2017 Black Policy Conference<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408205845/http://blackpolicyconference.com/|title=2017 Black Policy Conference Workshop: Black and Muslim: Organizing at the Intersection|date=April 8, 2017|website=blackpolicyconference.com|publisher=Harvard Kennedy School|access-date=October 27, 2018}}</ref> on the intersections of Black and Muslim identity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419192117/http://blackpolicyconference.com/speaker/blair-imani/|title=Blair Imani|date=April 8, 2017|website=blackpolicyconference.com|publisher=Harvard Kennedy School|access-date=October 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Imani appeared on ''[[Tucker Carlson Tonight]]'' where she advocated [[Safe-space|safe spaces]] on college campuses for Muslims, LGBT people, and other minorities, \"where you can be who you are without fear of being surveilled, having violence committed against you or being harassed\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Tucker Takes on Activist Who Supports Taxpayer-Funded Muslim 'Safe Spaces'|url=http://insider.foxnews.com/2017/06/09/tucker-carlson-vs-activist-who-supports-muslim-safe-spaces-australia|website=[[Fox News]]|accessdate=14 October 2017|date=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Imani appeared in [[Shavone Charles|SHAVONE.]]'s musical project titled \"4C\" with themes centered around the uplifment of black women, beauty [[diversity]] and [[the natural hair movement]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Espinoza|first1=Joshua|title= Shavone Celebrates Black Girl Magic in New \"4C\" Video|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/shavone-celebrates-black-girl-magic-020120960.html|date=March 28, 2019|website=yahoo.com|publisher=Yahoo! Entertainment|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Vel\u00e1zquez|first1=Devri|title= \u201c4C\u201d Is the Black Girl Magic Video You Didn\u2019t Know You Needed|url=https://www.naturallycurly.com/curlreading/coils/4c-is-the-black-girl-magic-video-you-didn-t-know-you-needed|date=April 8, 2019|website=naturallycurly.com|publisher=Naturally Curly|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nImani [[Coming out|came out]] as [[queer]] in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Imani|first1=Blair|title=Blair Imani gets real about queer Muslim representation, shares exclusive \"The Bold Type\" clip|url=https://www.glaad.org/blog/blair-imani-gets-real-about-queer-muslim-representation-shares-exclusive-bold-type-clip|website=[[GLAAD]]|accessdate=14 October 2017|date=24 August 2017}}</ref> After coming out, she said she received support \"from queer Muslims and young people all over the world\" and that she found solace in the representation of LGBT Muslims on ''[[The Bold Type]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McNamara|first1=Brittney|title=Blair Imani Opens Up About Being Queer, Black and Muslim|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/blair-imani-queer-muslim-woman|website=[[Teen Vogue]]|accessdate=14 October 2017|date=12 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.blairimani.com Personal website]\n\n{{Black Lives Matter}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Imani, Blair}}\n[[Category:Black Lives Matter people]]\n[[Category:21st-century African-American activists]]\n[[Category:African-American Muslims]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:LGBT Muslims]]\n[[Category:LGBT African Americans]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:African-American writers]]\n[[Category:Converts to Islam]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Blair Imani\n| birth_name = Blair Elizabeth Brown\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1993|10|31|mf=yes}}<ref name=birthdate>{{cite tweet |last= Imani |first=Blair |user=BlairImani |number=1056636517752422403 |date=October 28, 2018 |title= My birthday is on October 31, Halloween. I will be 25 this year.|access-date=October 29, 2018 }}</ref>\n| image = Blair Imani at LoveLoud 2018 (42462971960).jpg\n| caption = Blair Imani in 2018\n| education = [[Louisiana State University]]\n| known_for = Activism\n| movement = Black Lives Matter\n| website = https://blairimani.com\n}}\n\n'''Blair Imani''' (born '''Blair Elizabeth Brown''', October 31, 1993)<ref name=birthdate/> is an [[African-American]] [[Muslim]] [[queer]], author and [[activist]]. She was Executive Director of \"Equality for HER\", a now defunct feminist organisation.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Matthew|last=Corkins|url=http://observer.com/2017/02/blair-imani-black-muslim-activist-womens-march/|title=In Trump Era, Islam\u2019s Tolerance Helps Restless Activist Survive|date=February 19, 2017|work=Observer|access-date=April 18, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> She is a member of the [[Black Lives Matter]] movement, and is known for her voice on [[Twitter]] and [[Instagram]] and for protesting the [[shooting of Alton Sterling]] and [[Executive Order 13769]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/muslim-women-you-should-be-following-on-twitter-because-we-need-their-voices-now-more-than-ever-34101|title=Muslim Women You Should Be Following On Twitter, Because We Need Their Voices Now More Than Ever|last=Florio|first=Gina M.|work=Bustle|date=January 30, 2017|access-date=April 18, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Imani has written for ''[[HuffPost]]'' and ''[[Vice Media|VICE]].''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_us/article/why-activist-blair-imani-will-no-longer-wear-hijab-post-trump|title=Why activist Blair Imani will no longer wear hijab post-Trump|first=Blair|last=Imani|work=i-D|publisher=Vice Media|access-date=April 18, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/one-month-ago-in-baton-rouge_us_57a7d416e4b0c94bd3c9ce0c|title=One Month Ago In Baton Rouge|last=Imani|first=Blair|date=August 10, 2016|website=HuffPost|language=en-US|access-date=April 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nImani gained recognition for her arrest following the [[shooting of Alton Sterling]] in Baton Rouge, Louisiana, and her continued activism at the [[Intersectionality|intersection]] of [[Black people|Black]] and Muslim identity.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thefourohfive.com/culture/article/discussing-the-resistance-with-blair-imani-149|title=Discussing the Resistance with Blair Imani|last=Bynum-Reid|first=Dierra|work=The 405|access-date=April 18, 2017|date=March 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Education and career==\nImani graduated from [[Louisiana State University]] in 2015.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2016/07/14/baton-rouge-police-sued-arrest-peaceful-protesters/|title=Baton Rouge Police Sued Over Arrest of Peaceful Protesters|last=Mackey2016-07-14T15:35:14+00:00|first=Robert MackeyRobert|website=The Intercept|access-date=2017-04-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, she worked as a Press Officer for [[Planned Parenthood|Planned Parenthood Action Fund]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.plannedparenthoodaction.org/blog/donald-trump-bragged-about-sexual-assault-we-wont-let-him-normalize-it|title=Donald Trump Bragged About Sexual Assault \u2014 But We Won\u2019t Let Him Normalize It|website=www.plannedparenthoodaction.org|language=en|access-date=2017-04-18}}</ref> She is presently the Civic Action & Campaign Lead at [[Do Something|DoSomething.org]], the largest tech company exclusively for young people and social change.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dosomething.org/us/about/our-team|title=Our Team {{!}} DoSomething.org {{!}} Volunteer for Social Change|website=www.dosomething.org|language=en|access-date=2017-08-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/better/pop-culture/7-ways-be-better-activist-ncna791856|title=How to be an activist (no experience required)|work=NBC News|access-date=2017-08-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nImani is the author of ''Modern HERstory: Stories of Women and Nonbinary People Rewriting History'', published by [[Ten Speed Press]] on October 16, 2018. The book is illustrated by Monique Le and \"spotlights 70 overlooked but important [[people of color]], [[queer|queer people]], [[transgender|trans people]], [[disability|disabled people]], and more who are changing the world this very moment.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://penguinrandomhouseeducation.com/book/?isbn=9780399582240|title=Modern HERstory: Stories of Women and Nonbinary People Rewriting History|last=Imani|first=Blair|date=October 16, 2018|website=penguinrandomhouseeducation.com|publisher=Ten Speed Press|access-date=October 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glaad.org/blog/blair-imanis-modern-herstory-changes-narrative-social-justice-include-women-and-nonbinary|title=Blair Imani's \"Modern HERstory\" changes the narrative of social justice to include women and nonbinary notables|date=2018-11-27|website=GLAAD|language=en|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sanfranciscobookreview.com/product/modern-herstory-stories-of-women-and-nonbinary-people-rewriting-history/|title=Modern HERstory: Stories of Women and Nonbinary People Rewriting History|last=Winter|first=Kevin|website=[[San Francisco Book Review]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/life/2018/08/modern-herstory-unsung-activists/|title=\u2018Modern HERstory\u2019 Amplifies the Voices of Unsung Activists|last=Williams|first=Austin|date=August 8, 2018|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/authors-parents-go-celebrate-release-book-modern-herstory-cutest-thing-twitter-seen-015400116.html|title=Author's parents go all out to celebrate the release of her 'Modern HERstory' book, and it's the sweetest thing Twitter has seen|last=Schreiber|first=Hope|date=October 10, 2018|website=Yahoo Lifestyle|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.slj.com/?reviewDetail=modern-herstory-stories-of-women-and-nonbinary-people-rewriting-history|title=Modern HERstory: Stories of Women and Nonbinary People Rewriting History|last=Schembri|first=Pamela|website=School Library Journal|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref>\n\n==Activism in Baton Rouge==\n[[File:Blair_Imani_at_Baton_Rouge_Rally.jpg|thumb|290x290px|Blair Imani at Baton Rouge rally in protest of the police shooting of Alton Sterling]]\nOn July 10, 2016, in the aftermath of the shooting of Alton Sterling, Imani took part in a protest in [[Baton Rouge]], Louisiana. While peacefully protesting, she was arrested with her partner Akeem Muhammad.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/07/13/485895800/baton-rouge-protester-on-arrest-i-didnt-know-if-i-was-going-to-survive|title=Baton Rouge Protester On Arrest: 'I Didn't Know If I Was Going To Survive'|website=NPR.org|access-date=2017-04-18}}</ref> In an interview with ''The Intercept'', Imani detailed her encounter with Baton Rouge [[SWAT]] officers. She claimed that she was trampled and threatened verbally. She was photographed screaming as she was carried away by special force officers.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nWhile being detained, one officer ordered: \"really give it to her,\" and another officer removed her hijab.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Imani |first1=Blair |title=\"One Month Ago in Baton Rouge\" |url=http://www2.latech.edu/~bmagee/louisiana_anthology/texts/imani/imani--one-month-ago.html |website=Louisiana Anthology |accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nLess than a week after her arrest, Imani helped organize a vigil with the Louisiana State University Student Body Association in response to and in honor of the [[2016 shooting of Baton Rouge police officers|murder of three Baton Rouge police officers]]. In an article in ''[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]]'', she said, \"All violence is wrong,\" and that she is against all brutality, including violence against police officers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/news/baton_rouge_officer_shooting/article_e40669a4-4d3b-11e6-9bd9-378cde7cc0f8.html|title=Woman arrested in Alton Sterling protests is key organizer of fallen officers vigil|last=Allen|first=Rebekah|work=The Advocate|access-date=2017-04-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\n\n==Black and Muslim identity==\n\nImani converted to Islam in 2015 following feelings of discomfort in Christian churches and finding solace within Islam. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Hagen |first1=Sofie |title=\"60. Blair Imani - They Took My Hijab Away\" |url=https://mohpod.libsyn.com/60-blair-imani-they-took-my-hijab-away |website=Made of Human Podcast |accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nDescribing her decision to change her name, she explained that she chose the name Imani \"because Imani means 'my faith' and it's one of the days of Kwanzaa, it's also a Swahili word as well as an Arabic word, and I felt like it encapsulated my journey to Islam.\" <ref>{{cite web |last1=Aguilera |first1=Ramsey |title=\"Life as a Queer Muslim in 2019 with Blair Imani\" |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iUujhLMu-RY |website=Youtube |publisher=Youtube |accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the run up to the 2016 presidential election, Imani spoke about the intersection of Black and Muslim identity.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/602/the-sun-comes-up?act=6|title=Times Square|work=This American Life|access-date=2017-04-18}}</ref>\n\nImani waited one year after converting to wear the hijab<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hagen |first1=Sofie |title=\"60. Blair Imani - They Took My Hijab Away\" |url=https://mohpod.libsyn.com/60-blair-imani-they-took-my-hijab-away |website=Made of Human Podcast |accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref> \nand briefly stopped wearing it following the 2016 election.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Corkins |first1=Matthew |title=In Trump Era, Islam's Tolerance Helps Restless Activist Survive |url=https://observer.com/2017/02/blair-imani-black-muslim-activist-womens-march/ |website=Observer |publisher=Observer |accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe appeared on MSNBC's ''The Point'' hosted by Ari Melber on April 2, 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc-news/watch/growing-up-trump-the-next-generation-speaks-out-912401475510|title=Growing Up Trump: The next generation speaks out|work=MSNBC|access-date=2017-04-18}}</ref> She presented with activist [[Kwame Rose]] at the [[Harvard University]] [[John F. Kennedy School of Government|Kennedy School]]'s 2017 Black Policy Conference<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408205845/http://blackpolicyconference.com/|title=2017 Black Policy Conference Workshop: Black and Muslim: Organizing at the Intersection|date=April 8, 2017|website=blackpolicyconference.com|publisher=Harvard Kennedy School|access-date=October 27, 2018}}</ref> on the intersections of Black and Muslim identity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419192117/http://blackpolicyconference.com/speaker/blair-imani/|title=Blair Imani|date=April 8, 2017|website=blackpolicyconference.com|publisher=Harvard Kennedy School|access-date=October 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Imani appeared on ''[[Tucker Carlson Tonight]]'' where she advocated [[Safe-space|safe spaces]] on college campuses for Muslims, LGBT people, and other minorities, \"where you can be who you are without fear of being surveilled, having violence committed against you or being harassed\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Tucker Takes on Activist Who Supports Taxpayer-Funded Muslim 'Safe Spaces'|url=http://insider.foxnews.com/2017/06/09/tucker-carlson-vs-activist-who-supports-muslim-safe-spaces-australia|website=[[Fox News]]|accessdate=14 October 2017|date=9 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nImani [[Coming out|came out]] as [[queer]] in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Imani|first1=Blair|title=Blair Imani gets real about queer Muslim representation, shares exclusive \"The Bold Type\" clip|url=https://www.glaad.org/blog/blair-imani-gets-real-about-queer-muslim-representation-shares-exclusive-bold-type-clip|website=[[GLAAD]]|accessdate=14 October 2017|date=24 August 2017}}</ref> After coming out, she said she received support \"from queer Muslims and young people all over the world\" and that she found solace in the representation of LGBT Muslims on ''[[The Bold Type]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McNamara|first1=Brittney|title=Blair Imani Opens Up About Being Queer, Black and Muslim|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/blair-imani-queer-muslim-woman|website=[[Teen Vogue]]|accessdate=14 October 2017|date=12 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.blairimani.com Personal website]\n\n{{Black Lives Matter}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Imani, Blair}}\n[[Category:Black Lives Matter people]]\n[[Category:21st-century African-American activists]]\n[[Category:African-American Muslims]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:LGBT Muslims]]\n[[Category:LGBT African Americans]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:African-American writers]]\n[[Category:Converts to Islam]]\n", "name_user": "Ghostmihm", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBlack and Muslim identity:added \"4C\" music video", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blair_Imani"}
